[2026-05-20--17:10:37]User: You will be supplied with a Design Document, and Low Level Requirements
They have to follow this standard:

Software Design Policy (SDP)

The Objective of the Design Document is to Detail the Software Design in these Artifacts:
a. Component
b. State Machine
c. Additional Data

Document Structure
1. Findings are to be structured using XML files.
2. Only One Document is used to store all artifacts.
3. The Document must start with the <Design> tag.

Document Template
<Design>
    <Components>
    ...
    </Components>
    <StateMachines>
    ...
    </StateMachines>
    <AdditionalData>
    ...
    </AdditionalData>
</Design>

Component Structure
1. All components must be under the <Components> Tag
2. Each Components tag must have the version attribute, containing the version of the Artifact
3. Below the <Components> tag, every component must be stored inside its own <Component> tag.

4. Each component must have the following children
   a. <ID>: unique identifier for the component
   b. <Name> a descriptive name for the component
   c. <Purpose>: A detailed description of what the component does
   d. <ConnectedComponents>: All components that have some sort of connection to the component, inside <ConnectedComponent> tags. The ConnectedComponent tag must have these children
    d1. <Identifier>: The identifier of the connected component.
    d2. <Transmit>: All Signals that are transmitted by the connected component to the component, inside <Signal> tags. The Signal tag must have these children
        d2,1: <Name>: The identifier of the Signal
        d2,2 <Description>: Description of the Signal containing everything relevant for implementation
    d3. <Receive>: All Signals that are transmitted by the component to the connected component, inside <Signal> tags. The Signal tag must have these children
        d3,1: <Name>: The identifier of the Signal
        d3,2 <Description>: Description of the Signal containing everything relevant for implementation
   e. <Execution>: Description of the Conditions required for the components execution
   f. <Timing>: The timing constraints set onto the component, including execution frequency, in plain text.
   g. <Invariants>: All Invariants, in plain text.
   h. <Failures>: All Failure States including how to get to them, in plain text.
   i. <DerivedFrom>: All Low Level Requirements this Component is derived from

Component Template

<Components  version="{version}">
    <Component>
        <ID> {Identifier} </ID>
        <Name> {Name}  <Name>
        <Purpose> {Purpose} </Purpose>
        <ConnectedComponents>
            <ConnectedComponent>
                <Identifier> {Identifier} </Identifier>
                <Transmit>
                    <Signal>
                        <Name>{Signal Name}</Name>
                        <Description>{Signal Description}</Description>
                    </Signal>
                </Transmit>
                <Receive>
                    <Signal>
                        <Name>{Signal Name}</Name>
                        <Description>{Signal Description}</Description>
                    </Signal>
                </Receive>
            </ConnectedComponent>
        </ConnectedComponents>
        <Execution> {Execution Conditions} </Execution>
        <Timing> {Timing Constraints} </Timing>
        <Invariants> {Invariants} </Invariants>
        <Failures> {Failures} </Failures>
        <DerivedFrom> {Requirements} </DerivedFrom>
    </Component>
</Components>

State Machine Structure
1. All State Machines must be under the <StateMachines> Tag
2. Each State Machines tag must have the version attribute, containing the version of the Artifact
3. Below the <StateMachines> tag, every state machine must be stored inside its own <StateMachine> tag.

4. Each State Machine must have the following children
    a. <ID>: unique identifier for the State Machine
    b. <OfComponent>: reference to the component that own the State Machine
    c. <States> :All possible States, inside <State> tags. The State tag must have these children
        c1. <Name>: The Name of the State
        c2. <StateAction>: Optional: The Action performed when the state is active
    d. <Transitions>: All possible Transitions between States, inside <Transition> tags. The Transition tag must have these children
        d1. <From>: The State the transition starts in
        d2. <To>: The State the transitions ends in
        d3. <Trigger>: The Event that needs to happen for the transition to start, explained
        d4. <Guard>: Optional: Conditions that need to be met for the transition to start, explained
        d5. <TransitionAction>: Optional: The Action performed when the transition happens
    e. <DerivedFrom>: All Low Level Requirements this State Machine is derived from

State Machine Template

<StateMachines  version="{version}">
    <StateMachine>
        <ID> {Identifier} </ID>
        <OfComponent>{Component}</OfComponent>
        <States>
            <State>
                <Name>{Name}</Name>
                <StateAction>{Action}</StateAction>
            </State>
        </States>
        <Transitions>
            <Transition>
                <From>{From State}</From>
                <To>{To State}</To>
                <Trigger>{Trigger}</Trigger>
                <Guard>{Guard}</Guard>
                <TransitionAction>{Action}</TransitionAction>
            </Transition>
        </Transitions>
        <DerivedFrom> {Requirements} </DerivedFrom>
    </StateMachine>
</StateMachines>

Additional Data Structure
1. Additional Data must be under the <AdditionalData> Tag
2. Each additional data tag must have the version attribute, containing the version of the Artifact
3. Below the <AdditionalData> tag, every bit of data must be stored inside its own <Data> tag.

4.  Each Data point must have the following children
    a. <ID>: unique identifier for the Data Point
    b. <Content>: The content of the data, describing everything needed for implementation
    c. <DerivedFrom>: All Low Level Requirements this Data is derived from

<AdditionalData  version="{version}">
    <Data>
        <ID> {Identifier} </ID>
        <Content>
            {Content}
        </Content>
        <DerivedFrom> {Requirements}</DerivedFrom>
    </Data>
</AdditionalData>

Identification
  The content of the artifacts <ID> tag must conform to the pattern:
  "{type}--{counter}"
  "type": The type of artifact: "CMP": Component, "FSM": State Machine, "DAT": Additional Data
  "counter": The number of the artifact in its category, starting with 1


Differentiation

All software components need to be structured into the Component Artifact, to describe their behaviour State Machines are used.
Information from the LLRs that do not fit into either Artifact type are to be put into the additional data Artifact. 

You will check them and whenever there are errors, either regarding this document or any logical faults you will create Findings according to this document:

Software Findings Policy (SFP)

When a Verifier notices an Error or Inconsistency in any Document a Finding is created, which details the Error, Its location and a possible solution.
The creator of the Original Document has to process each Finding and either implement the solution, or justify why the problem does not need to be fixed.

Findings Document Structure
1. Findings are to be structured using XML files.
2. A Findings Document always contain findings of only one document
3. All documents must start with the <Findings> tag.
4. The <Findings> tag must have three attributes:
   a. “version”: the findings documents version
   b. “source”: specifies the type of document the findings reference
   c. “source_version”: specifies the version of the source document

Findings Structure
6.  Below the <Findings> tag, every finding must be stored inside its own <Finding> tag.
    a. each finding must have the attribute "id"

7. Each Finding must have the following children
    a. <ItemID> The ID of the Item the Finding references
    b. <Description> Description of the Finding
    c. <Solution> A Suggestion as how to fix the Problem
    d. <Severity> Severity how the finding

8. Findings can have the following children, in certain circumstances
    e <RollbackPhase> to which phase the development needs to be rolled back to fix the findings

Finding Template

<Findings version="{version}" source= "{source}" source_version = "{source_version}"  >
    <Finding ID = "{finding id}">
        <ItemID> {RequirementID} </ItemID>
        <Severity> {Severity} </Severity>
        <Description> {Description} </Description>
        <Solution> {Solution} </Solution>
        <RollbackPhase> {Optional: Rollback Phase}</RollbackPhase>
    </Finding>
</Findings>

Identification
  The content of the findings <ID> tag must conform to the pattern:
  "{source_type}--{source_version}--{counter}"
  "source_type": The type of the source document
  "source_version": The version of the source document
  "counter": The number of the finding of the document, starting with 1

Severity
    Severity can have 3 Grades
    a. "Minor": Only affects one item, minor changes needed in the current phase
    b. "Major": Affects multiple items, major changes needed in the current phase
    c. "Catastrophic": Affects multiple items, it is necessary to change items in prior phases

    Whenever a catastrophic finding is detected, only catastrophic findings are to be documented.
    Catastrophic findings need to have the Rollback Phase child, indicating to which phase the process needs to be rolled back to fix the problem.
    It is advised to only roll back to the previous phase, but it is possible to rollback multiple phases
    The phases are as follows:
    a. "High Level Requirements"
    b. "Low Level Requirements"
    c. "Design"
    d. "Implementation"



Answer Document Structure
1. Answers are to be structured using XML files.
2. A Answer Document contains only the answer to one Findings document
3. All documents must start with the <Answer> tag.
4. The <Findings> tag must have one attributes:
   b. “findings_version”: specifies the version of the findings document, the answer is to
   c. “findings_type”: specifies the type of document the finding document references

Findings Structure
5. Below the <Findings> tag, every answer must be stored inside its own <Justification> or <Implementation> tag.

Justification Structure
6. Each Justification must have the following children
    a. <FindingID> The ID of the Finding the Answer references
    b. <Explanation> Explanation why the Finding does not need to be fixed

Implementation Structure
7. Each Implementation must have the following children
    a. <FindingID> The ID of the Finding the Answer references
    b. <Explanation> Explanation of how the Finding was Fixed

<Answer findings_version= "{findings_version}" findings_type "{findings_type}">
    <Justification>
        <FindingID> {Finding ID} </FindingID>
        <Explanation> {Explanation} </Explanation>
    </Justification>

    <Implementation>
        <FindingID> {Finding ID} </FindingID>
        <Solution> {Solution} </Solution>
    </Implementation>
</Answer>

Justification
    A Justification is needed whenever a Finding is not Accepted, it needs to explain why the Finding is not correct
    When the Finding Author does not agree with the Justification, another Finding, referencing the same Item as the original Finding needs to be created, arguing against the Justification

 

When you got a design document, to verify and you found no problems only answer with "clear" otherwise answer with the findings as laid out before. When you got no design document, only instructions answer with check if you understood your task, and help if you have problems.


