[2026-05-20--17:15:12]Agent: <Findings version="1" source="Design" source_version="1">
    <Finding ID="Design--1--1">
        <ItemID>CMP--4</ItemID>
        <Severity>Minor</Severity>
        <Description>
The Motion Controller component uses the signal name &quot;MC_PathExecutionStatus&quot; for the status it TRANSMITS to Mission Control, while the Mission Control component defines &quot;MC_PathExecutionStatus&quot; as the signal it RECEIVES. According to the overall naming pattern in the document, signals initiated by the Motion Controller towards Mission Control should have a prefix that indicates the sender (e.g. &quot;MCtrl_&quot; or &quot;MC4_&quot;). As written, the directionality is ambiguous and breaks the otherwise clear convention where &quot;MC_...&quot; denotes signals initiated by Mission Control.
        </Description>
        <Solution>
Rename the status signal transmitted by CMP--4 to a name that clearly indicates Motion Controller as the sender (for example &quot;MCtrl_PathExecutionStatus&quot; or &quot;MC4_PathExecutionStatus&quot;). Then update CMP--1 (Mission Control) to RECEIVE this renamed signal instead of &quot;MC_PathExecutionStatus&quot;, ensuring consistency between the two components’ Transmit/Receive descriptions.
        </Solution>
    </Finding>

    <Finding ID="Design--1--2">
        <ItemID>CMP--4</ItemID>
        <Severity>Minor</Severity>
        <Description>
The Motion Controller’s ConnectedComponents section defines a connection to CMP--3 (Cell-Based Path Planner) with a transmitted signal &quot;MC_CurrentPathFeedback&quot;, but the corresponding Receive side in CMP--3 neither references this signal nor CMP--4 as a connected component. This creates an asymmetrical interface definition: CMP--4 indicates a dependency that CMP--3 does not acknowledge, and the purpose of that signal is described only as &quot;optional&quot;.
        </Description>
        <Solution>
Either:
(1) If planner feedback from Motion Controller is actually required, add a matching ConnectedComponent entry in CMP--3 with a Receive signal definition for &quot;MC_CurrentPathFeedback&quot; (or better, rename this signal to a planner-centric prefix such as &quot;PP_CurrentPathFeedback&quot; to match other naming), and clarify how planner uses this information; or
(2) If the feedback is not required, remove the CMP--3 ConnectedComponent and &quot;MC_CurrentPathFeedback&quot; signal from CMP--4 to keep the interface set minimal and symmetric.
        </Solution>
    </Finding>

    <Finding ID="Design--1--3">
        <ItemID>CMP--1</ItemID>
        <Severity>Minor</Severity>
        <Description>
In the Execution description for Mission Control in the RETURN_TO_START state, the text states: &quot;Monitor MC_PathExecutionStatus; when EXECUTION COMPLETED and current_cell == start_cell, declare return path complete...&quot;. The defined ExecutionState enumeration in DAT--1 uses the value &quot;COMPLETED&quot;, not &quot;EXECUTION COMPLETED&quot;. Using a non-enumerated value is inconsistent and may cause implementation ambiguity.
        </Description>
        <Solution>
Replace the phrase &quot;when EXECUTION COMPLETED and current_cell == start_cell&quot; with &quot;when execution_state == COMPLETED and current_cell == start_cell&quot; to align with the ExecutionState enumeration defined in DAT--1.
        </Solution>
    </Finding>

    <Finding ID="Design--1--4">
        <ItemID>CMP--2</ItemID>
        <Severity>Minor</Severity>
        <Description>
The DerivedFrom section of the Frontier Generation and Exploration Target Selection component lists the requirement ID &quot;LL--MAP--1.1.6&quot; repeated multiple times on separate lines:
&quot;LL--MAP--1.1.6; LL--MAP--1.1.6; ...&quot;. This is redundant and makes the traceability unnecessarily noisy without adding information.
        </Description>
        <Solution>
Deduplicate the DerivedFrom list for CMP--2 so that each requirement ID, including LL--MAP--1.1.6, appears only once. Ensure the final list contains the unique set of LLR IDs from which this component is derived.
        </Solution>
    </Finding>

    <Finding ID="Design--1--5">
        <ItemID>CMP--3</ItemID>
        <Severity>Minor</Severity>
        <Description>
The Cell-Based Path Planner’s ConnectedComponents section does not mention CMP--4 (Motion Controller), whereas CMP--4 refers to CMP--3 and describes receiving &quot;PP_PathResponse&quot; &quot;provided indirectly via Mission Control&quot;. This leads to an inconsistent view of data flow: if the path always goes MC → CMP--4, there should be no direct CMP--3↔CMP--4 connection; if there is a direct connection, it must be described symmetrically in both components.
        </Description>
        <Solution>
Clarify the topology: 
- If all PP_PathResponse messages are delivered only to Mission Control, remove the CMP--3 ConnectedComponent from CMP--4 (and the related description) to reflect that the Motion Controller never directly interacts with the planner.
- If a direct interaction is desired, add a corresponding ConnectedComponent in CMP--3 that Transmits/Receives the relevant signals to/from CMP--4 and specify the exact data exchanged.
        </Solution>
    </Finding>

    <Finding ID="Design--1--6">
        <ItemID>CMP--4</ItemID>
        <Severity>Minor</Severity>
        <Description>
The Motion Controller’s Invariants state that &quot;Active path is always a subset of FREE cells and respects PRESENT walls (enforced by planner).&quot; However, the design also allows the Motion Controller to execute &quot;wall avoidance maneuvers&quot; that could potentially deviate from the path cells produced by the planner. The current text does not clearly state whether these avoidance maneuvers are constrained to remain within FREE cells and not cross PRESENT walls, which can lead to ambiguity about safety and adherence to LL--MAP--1.4.4 and LL--PLAN--1.1.1.
        </Description>
        <Solution>
Explicitly refine the Execution and/or Invariants of CMP--4 to state that:
- Any avoidance maneuver trajectory must still keep the robot center within FREE cells (or at least within areas that do not intersect BLOCKED cells or PRESENT walls when inflated by robot radius plus margin M).
- The Motion Controller shall not command motion that requires crossing a PRESENT wall boundary, even during avoidance.
This makes the relation between planner guarantees and local avoidance explicit and traceable to the mapping and planning LLRs.
        </Solution>
    </Finding>

    <Finding ID="Design--1--7">
        <ItemID>CMP--11</ItemID>
        <Severity>Minor</Severity>
        <Description>
The Sensor Abstraction and Filtering Layer Execution section describes sampling ultrasonics and IR, filtering, invalid-reading handling, and front-wall proximity thresholding and hysteresis, but it does not explicitly mention applying the sampling rate and jitter constraints from LL--RELIAB--1.2.1 (rate in [10,50] Hz, default 20 Hz, jitter tolerance) beyond a brief reference in Timing. The behavior regarding jitter handling is left implicit.
        </Description>
        <Solution>
Augment CMP--11’s Execution or Timing section to explicitly state:
- The sampling rate used (f) is configured via Reliability/Safety (CMP--16) and must satisfy 10 Hz ≤ f ≤ 50 Hz, with default f = 20 Hz.
- SAL samples exactly once per control-loop iteration, and the scheduler ensures jitter does not exceed the specified tolerance; SAL will use the provided timebase/period to detect and optionally log excessive jitter.
This makes the implementation responsibilities clearer against LL--RELIAB--1.2.1.
        </Solution>
    </Finding>

    <Finding ID="Design--1--8">
        <ItemID>DAT--1</ItemID>
        <Severity>Minor</Severity>
        <Description>
The Additional Data enumeration definitions in DAT--1 include CellState, WallState, MissionState, PathRequestType, PlannerStatus, ExecutionState, and SecondRunResult. The LLRs also imply several other enumerations or symbolic values (for example EXPLORATION_COMPLETED vs EXPLORATION_TIMEOUT events, state machine event types, sensor validity flags) that are used in the component descriptions but not explicitly listed here. This reduces completeness of the central enumeration specification.
        </Description>
        <Solution>
Extend DAT--1 to include additional enumerations used across components, such as:
- ExplorationEventType = {EXPLORATION_COMPLETED, EXPLORATION_TIMEOUT}
- InitStatus = {INIT_PENDING, INIT_COMPLETED}
- Maybe SensorValidity = {VALID, INVALID} if represented as an enum rather than plain bools
and any other repeatedly used symbolic event types. This improves centralization of protocol and state definitions.
        </Solution>
    </Finding>

    <Finding ID="Design--1--9">
        <ItemID>FSM--1</ItemID>
        <Severity>Minor</Severity>
        <Description>
In FSM--1, the EXPLORE→RETURN_TO_START transition trigger correctly refers to EXPLORATION_COMPLETED and EXPLORATION_TIMEOUT events, but the RETURN_TO_START→SECOND_RUN transition guard includes &quot;Exploration status indicates map completeness&quot; without an explicit reference to how this is represented (map completeness flag, event history, or Exploration-Status module state). This could lead to an implementation that re-queries the map and misinterprets timeouts vs completion, conflicting with LL--RUN--1.2.1, which requires SECOND_RUN only after completion (not timeout-only).
        </Description>
        <Solution>
Clarify the guard for RETURN_TO_START→SECOND_RUN in FSM--1 to reference a specific, already-defined state or flag, for example:
- &quot;Guard: last exploration termination event type == EXPLORATION_COMPLETED (not TIMEOUT) as stored in Mission Control’s internal mission status&quot;.
This removes ambiguity between using map completeness directly vs using Exploration-Status events and aligns precisely with the LLR semantics.
        </Solution>
    </Finding>
</Findings>
